//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: not a compile-time constant
//
// A `const` initialiser is evaluated by the compiler, so it admits exactly what
// `ir::opt`'s folder folds: literals, other consts, and integer and boolean arithmetic
// over those. String concatenation is the interesting rejection — it looks every bit as
// constant as `1 + 2` to a reader, and is refused because `fold_int`/`fold_bool` are the
// whole of the folder and neither touches `str`.
//
// The failure mode this prevents is silent rather than loud. An initialiser the folder
// declines still compiles and still runs; it just becomes a `neon_str_concat` executed at
// every use of the constant, which is the opposite of what `const` promises.

use std::io;

const GREETING: str = "hello" + " world"

fn main() {
    io::println(GREETING);
}
